{
  "query": "What are the benefits for butterflies and moths of reducing or eliminating chemical inputs on farmland?",
  "relevant_summary": "Reducing the use of fertilizers, pesticides, or herbicides can be beneficial for butterflies and moths. Eight studies found that areas with reduced or no chemical inputs, sometimes in combination with other agri-environment schemes, had a greater species richness of adult butterflies, moths, or caterpillars (3897). Similarly, six studies found that less intensively managed grasslands, which often involves reduced chemical use, had a higher species richness of butterflies and moths (3958). In some cases, even when overall species richness was similar, unfertilized grasslands supported a greater richness of specialist moths (3897). Low-input grasslands were also found to support more butterfly species whose caterpillars are specialized, feeding on a single host plant (3958).\n\nIn terms of population numbers, six studies observed that areas with less frequent or no chemical applications had a higher abundance of adult butterflies, moths, or caterpillars (3897). On permanent grasslands, reducing management intensity, which can include stopping chemical applications, led to an increase in the abundance of large moths in one study (3958), and higher abundance of butterflies, micro-moths, and declining macro-moths in three other studies (3958). However, some studies found no difference in species richness (3897, 3958) or abundance (3897) with reduced chemical inputs. Additionally, one study noted that while some moth species preferred less fertilized grasslands, a larger number of species preferred more heavily fertilized areas (3897).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3897",
