{
  "query": "What is the state of the evidence regarding the effectiveness of agri-environment schemes for butterfly and moth conservation across Europe?",
  "relevant_summary": "Thirty-two studies evaluated the effects of paying farmers to cover the costs of conservation measures for butterflies and moths (3915). \n\nIn terms of species richness and diversity, twelve of fifteen studies in Switzerland, the UK, and Sweden found that areas managed under agri-environment schemes had higher butterfly and moth species richness or diversity than conventional fields or farms (3915). One replicated, randomized, controlled study in the UK found that spring barley undersown with a mix of grasses and legumes had a higher species richness of butterflies than extensively or conventionally managed grassland (3926). However, three studies found species richness to be similar between areas in agri-environment schemes and those not (3915), and one replicated, site comparison study in Switzerland found that farms with a larger area of in-field agri-environment scheme options, including undersown cereals, had a similar species richness of butterflies to farms with a smaller area of such schemes (3926). One Finnish study found that grassland managed under an agri-environment scheme had lower species richness of butterflies and day-flying moths than abandoned, unmanaged grassland (3915).\n\nRegarding abundance, seventeen of nineteen studies in the UK, Sweden, Switzerland, and Germany reported higher abundance of butterflies and moths in areas managed under agri-environment schemes compared to unmanaged woodland or conventional farms (3915). A UK study also found that undersown spring barley had a higher abundance of butterflies than extensively or conventionally managed grassland (3926). Conversely, three studies in Finland and the Czech Republic found that grasslands under agri-environment schemes had a lower abundance of most butterfly and day-flying moth species compared to unmanaged grassland (3915). A study in Switzerland found that farms with larger areas of in-field agri-environment schemes, like undersown cereals, had similar butterfly abundance to farms with smaller areas of these schemes (3926).\n\nOne UK study reported that providing advice to landowners about applying for an agri-environment scheme resulted in 82% of them submitting applications, with over 3,000 ha of farmland consequently being managed for the marsh fritillary butterfly (3846).",
  "action_ids": [
