{"query":"In US prairies, how do different management techniques like grazing, mowing (haying), and prescribed burning compare in their effects on butterfly abundance?","summary":"In US prairies, the effects of management techniques on butterfly abundance vary. Prairies managed by haying showed a higher abundance of prairie specialist butterflies and a lower abundance of generalist and migrant butterflies when compared to prairies managed by burning (3945, 3882). Specifically, two prairie specialist species, the regal fritillary and arogos skipper, were found to be less abundant in prairies managed by burning than in those managed by haying or in grazed pastures (3882). The abundance of Karner blue butterflies on oak savannas managed by mowing was found to be similar to unmanaged savannas or those managed by burning (3945).

Prescribed burning has shown mixed results. The abundance of Fender’s blue butterfly caterpillars and eggs was higher in prairies one or more years after management by burning compared to grazed land (3882). Conversely, the abundance of regal fritillary adults was lower on prairies managed by burning than on unburned land (3882). One study found that pastures managed with patch-burning had a lower species richness of butterflies than rotationally grazed pastures but a higher richness than continuously grazed pastures (3882).

Under rotational burning regimes, the time since the last fire is a key factor. The abundance of prairie specialist butterflies was higher on prairies that had been burned more than one, two, or four years prior compared to those burned more recently (3883). The abundance of grassland and generalist butterflies peaked in the third year after a fire, while migrant butterflies were most abundant in the first year (3883). However, for some fritillary species, abundance was lower in prairies managed with rotational burning compared to prairies managed with only haying or grazing, or unmanaged prairies (3883). Combining rotational burning with grazing was found to create a different butterfly community composition than either management practice used alone (3883).","action_ids":["3882","3945","3883"]}

